Overall, postpartum counselling shows consistent growth, while postpartum acceptors experience small declines and one temporary dip in early 2025."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"edb8e928-a4fd-48b2-af3f-2a7c157ac955","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Quarter-to-quarter change in service volume post partum family planning indicators"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"ANC1 visits were consistently above expectations in 2025, averaging ~26,900 per month vs. ~24,200 expected (~11% higher), with June 2025 ~26,200 visits (~9% above expected), and a smaller but still positive surplus again in September 2025, when ANC1 remained above expected levels.

ANC4 visits stayed close to expected levels, averaging ~19,300 per month vs. ~18,800 expected (~3% higher), with June 2025 ~18,900 visits (~5% above expected).

Both indicators align with expected trends, though ANC1 shows clearer gains. Continuity remains a concern, as fewer women complete ANC4 compared to ANC1."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"b32538b0-928a-466c-95b1-6ff2ebbff03c","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"ANC1 shows slight surpluses in 2025, while ANC4 stays near trend, but continuity gap remains"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"ANC1 visits were slightly above expectations in 2025, averaging ~26,900 vs. ~24,200 expected (~11% higher). 

Iron–folate provision (ANC IFA) showed larger surpluses in 2025, with an average surplus of ~17% above expected levels. Monthly surpluses ranged widely—some exceeding 20–30%—reflecting higher-than-expected supplementation but also irregular month-to-month patterns.

HIV testing at first ANC visit remained close to expected volumes since 2024."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"04c3b75e-60e1-45ee-a603-fef46bd0776e","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"ANC visits and HIV screening align with expectations, while iron–folate supplementation exceeds expected levels"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Newborn PNC visits rose above expected levels in 2025, reaching ~22,700–22,900 by May–June, which corresponds to surpluses of ~14–15%.

Maternal PNC visits showed a very similar pattern, rising to ~23,300 in May and ~22,900 in June, equivalent to surpluses of ~14% above expected levels.

Across 2025, PNC for newborns consistently reached ~97–99% of maternal PNC volumes, showing strong alignment between mother and newborn follow-up. However, both remained slightly below delivery volumes, indicating modest gaps in completing timely postpartum care for all mothers and babies."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"2ff8805a-0463-464f-84e3-36c6dae098b8","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"PNC visits rise above expected levels in 2025"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"After tracking near expected levels early in 2025, BCG rose above trend in Q2. Surpluses strengthened from ~13% in Q2 to ~16% in Q3, signaling continued improvements in newborn vaccination.

Penta1 volumes stayed close to expected throughout 2025, with June reaching ~28,900 doses (~7% above expected)—consistent with trend rather than a major surplus. By Q3 2025, Penta1 remained aligned with expected levels but increased slightly to ~9% above expected, reflecting modest improvement.

Penta3 similarly tracked expectations for most of the period but showed sharper increases around late 2024 and early 2025 from catch-up or campaigns. In 2025, surpluses rose from ~7% in Q2 to ~10% in Q3, indicating a gradual strengthening in third-dose completion."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"fb3f7d80-0796-46ae-9009-350bb33a615a","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Immunization services strengthen in 2025, with gains in BCG and Penta3"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"The number of malaria-positive cases dropped sharply in mid-2024, with volumes ~25–32% below expected in March–April and remaining depressed through much of the year. By 2025, detected cases rose again, returning closer to expected levels by June (~2% below trend).

ACT treatment closely followed the trend in positive cases, with marked declines in 2024 and higher volumes in 2025. By June 2025, treatment levels remained somewhat close to expected, and the close alignment with positive cases indicates that most detected cases continued to be treated.

Malaria typically rises during the rainy season, but timing and peak sharpness vary by district. The model captures seasonality at the national level, but does not fully reflect these local differences."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"6dabd0e2-b4c1-46a6-890e-62007b79eac3","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Malaria-positive cases and treatment fell in 2023–24, with increased detection in 2025"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"At the national level, the mean DQA score improved from 94% in 2019 to 95% in 2025. National mean scores are high, showing that on average, Sierra Leone's HMIS data is close to the desired quality standard.

Across most districts, all scores remained above 80% in 2025. Except for Western Area Rural District at 76%.

Although many facility-months don’t meet all criteria, they are close on average — suggesting that small improvements in reporting practices could bring most facilities above the threshold."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"083efb2d-ed4e-43ec-8386-1403fedff17f","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in data quality"}}

