{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"In 2025, institutional deliveries rose steadily above expected levels, with volumes reaching ~24,200–24,600 in May–June. This corresponds to surpluses of ~14% in May and ~14–16% in June, showing clear gains in the uptake of facility-based births.

Deliveries attended by skilled health personnel followed the same pattern. Skilled attendance reached ~24,400 in May and ~23,800 in June, representing surpluses of ~12% above expected levels.

Across 2025, both indicators moved closely together with delivery_sba consistently within ~1–3% of total institutional deliveries."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"f1da657b-24d4-4e1d-9d5a-85706d2d1a55","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Institutional deliveries and skilled health attendance rise above expected levels in 2025"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"The number of malaria-positive cases dropped sharply in mid-2024, with volumes ~25–32% below expected in March–April and remaining depressed through much of the year. By 2025, detected cases rose again, returning closer to expected levels by June (~2% below trend).

ACT treatment closely followed the trend in positive cases, with marked declines in 2024 and higher volumes in 2025. By June 2025, treatment levels remained somewhat close to expected, and the close alignment with positive cases indicates that most detected cases continued to be treated.

Malaria typically rises during the rainy season, but timing and peak sharpness vary by district. The model captures seasonality at the national level, but does not fully reflect these local differences."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"6dabd0e2-b4c1-46a6-890e-62007b79eac3","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Malaria-positive cases and treatment fell in 2023–24, with increased detection in 2025"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"Institutional deliveries and deliveries attended by skilled health personnel grew strongly in Q2 2025, reaching their highest levels in the series. This elevated level was maintained in Q3 2025, with both indicators remaining similarly high quarter-to-quarter.

The ~15% increase observed in Q3 2025 reflects continued strong performance in Q2, indicating sustained uptake of facility-based births and skilled attendance.","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"05ce0387-5217-4d97-a301-83a8412c5b84","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Quarter-to-quarter change in service volume 
Deliveries","useFooter":false,"footerText":""}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"In 2025, institutional deliveries rose steadily above expected levels, with volumes reaching ~24,200–24,600 in May–June. This corresponds to surpluses of ~14% in May and ~14–16% in June, showing clear gains in the uptake of facility-based births.

Deliveries attended by skilled health personnel followed the same pattern. Skilled attendance reached ~24,400 in May and ~23,800 in June, representing surpluses of ~12% above expected levels.

Across 2025, both indicators moved closely together with delivery_sba consistently within ~1–3% of total institutional deliveries."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"f1da657b-24d4-4e1d-9d5a-85706d2d1a55","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Institutional deliveries and skilled health attendance rise above expected levels in 2025"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"ANC1 volumes trended upward from late 2024, peaking around March–May 2025 near 29,000 visits, and then stabilizing just below 28,000.

ANC4 showed slower but steady growth, reaching about 20,000 visits by mid-2025 — consistently ~8–9k lower than ANC1, indicating incomplete progression through visits.

Addressing gaps between first and fourth visits remains critical to ensure continuity of care and improved antenatal outcomes.","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"25641e45-d92c-48e9-b681-9d00af2681b4","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in antenatal care","useFooter":false,"footerText":""}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"At the national level, data completeness is very high, with most indicators consistently above 95%.

However, a few indicators — notably infectious diseases and nutrition— have much lower completeness (below 80%), which may affect reliability for those services.

These patterns suggest the main challenge is indicator-specific reporting gaps rather than district performance, highlighting areas where data quality strengthening is most needed."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"e8c495f4-7fbb-47f5-bfe7-c83002dd25a2","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false},"hideFigureCaption":true,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Reporting completeness"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"At the national level, outliers are very low, with most indicators averaging below 1%, suggesting consistent reporting quality.

Across districts, most indicators remain stable, with limited outliers.

Notably, antenatal clients given iron folate, family planning indicators, and deworming treatments for children have a higher proportion of outliers than other indicators."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.6,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"996f05ed-4b56-4efe-8990-bc363d7568a9","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Outliers"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Newborn PNC visits rose above expected levels in 2025, reaching ~22,700–22,900 by May–June, which corresponds to surpluses of ~14–15%.

Maternal PNC visits showed a very similar pattern, rising to ~23,300 in May and ~22,900 in June, equivalent to surpluses of ~14% above expected levels.

Across 2025, PNC for newborns consistently reached ~97–99% of maternal PNC volumes, showing strong alignment between mother and newborn follow-up. However, both remained slightly below delivery volumes, indicating modest gaps in completing timely postpartum care for all mothers and babies."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"2ff8805a-0463-464f-84e3-36c6dae098b8","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"PNC visits rise above expected levels in 2025"}}
